Task 2: Use iptables for Packet Filtering and Forwarding
Subtask 2.1: Configure Basic iptables Rules
Step 1: Check current iptables rules

sudo iptables -L -n -v
Step 2: Create a backup of current iptables rules

sudo iptables-save > ~/iptables_backup.rules
Step 3: Flush existing rules (be careful in production environments)

sudo iptables -F
sudo iptables -X
sudo iptables -t nat -F
sudo iptables -t nat -X
Step 4: Set default policies

sudo iptables -P INPUT DROP
sudo iptables -P FORWARD DROP
sudo iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT
Subtask 2.2: Configure Traffic Filtering Rules
Step 1: Allow loopback traffic

sudo iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT
sudo iptables -A OUTPUT -o lo -j ACCEPT
Step 2: Allow established and related connections

sudo iptables -A INPUT -m conntrack --ctstate ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
Step 3: Allow SSH (important for remote access)

sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT
Step 4: Allow HTTP and HTTPS traffic

sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT
sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j ACCEPT
Step 5: Create custom chain for C2 traffic filtering

sudo iptables -N C2_FILTER
sudo iptables -A INPUT -j C2_FILTER
Step 6: Add rules to log and allow specific C2 traffic

# Log suspicious traffic patterns
sudo iptables -A C2_FILTER -p tcp --dport 8080 -m string --string "RedTeamAgent" --algo bm -j LOG --log-prefix "C2_TRAFFIC: "

# Allow C2 traffic from localhost
sudo iptables -A C2_FILTER -p tcp --dport 8080 -s 127.0.0.1 -j ACCEPT

# Drop other traffic to C2 port
sudo iptables -A C2_FILTER -p tcp --dport 8080 -j DROP
Subtask 2.3: Configure Port Forwarding and NAT
Step 1: Enable IP forwarding

echo 'net.ipv4.ip_forward=1' | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.conf
sudo sysctl -p
Step 2: Set up port forwarding for additional obfuscation

# Forward traffic from port 8443 to our Nginx redirector
sudo iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp --dport 8443 -j REDIRECT --to-port 80

# Forward specific traffic to different ports based on source
sudo iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp --dport 9090 -s 127.0.0.1 -j REDIRECT --to-port 8080
Step 3: Configure MASQUERADE for outbound traffic

sudo iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o eth0 -j MASQUERADE
Subtask 2.4: Create iptables Persistence Script
Step 1: Create a script to save and restore iptables rules

nano ~/iptables_manager.sh
Step 2: Add the following script content

#!/bin/bash

RULES_FILE="/etc/iptables/rules.v4"

case "$1" in
    save)
        echo "Saving iptables rules..."
        sudo mkdir -p /etc/iptables
        sudo iptables-save | sudo tee $RULES_FILE > /dev/null
        echo "Rules saved to $RULES_FILE"
        ;;
    restore)
        echo "Restoring iptables rules..."
        if [ -f "$RULES_FILE" ]; then
            sudo iptables-restore < $RULES_FILE
            echo "Rules restored from $RULES_FILE"
        else
            echo "No rules file found at $RULES_FILE"
        fi
        ;;
    status)
        echo "Current iptables rules:"
        sudo iptables -L -n -v --line-numbers
        echo ""
        echo "NAT table rules:"
        sudo iptables -t nat -L -n -v --line-numbers
        ;;
    *)
        echo "Usage: $0 {save|restore|status}"
        exit 1
        ;;
esac
Step 3: Make the script executable and save current rules

chmod +x ~/iptables_manager.sh
./iptables_manager.sh save
Task 3: Configure Tor Hidden Services for Encrypted Traffic
Subtask 3.1: Install and Configure Tor
Step 1: Install Tor

sudo apt install tor -y
Step 2: Create a backup of the Tor configuration

sudo cp /etc/tor/torrc /etc/tor/torrc.backup
Step 3: Configure Tor hidden service

sudo nano /etc/tor/torrc
Step 4: Add the following configuration to the file

# Uncomment and modify these lines
SocksPort 9050
ControlPort 9051
CookieAuthentication 1

# Hidden service configuration
HiddenServiceDir /var/lib/tor/c2_service/
HiddenServicePort 80 127.0.0.1:80
HiddenServicePort 443 127.0.0.1:443

# Additional hidden service for direct C2 access
HiddenServiceDir /var/lib/tor/direct_c2/
HiddenServicePort 8080 127.0.0.1:8080

# Security settings
HiddenServiceVersion 3
ExitPolicy reject *:*
Step 5: Set proper permissions and restart Tor

sudo systemctl restart tor
sudo systemctl enable tor
Step 6: Wait for Tor to generate hidden service addresses

sleep 10
sudo cat /var/lib/tor/c2_service/hostname
sudo cat /var/lib/tor/direct_c2/hostname
